value.0: A young boy garbed in the black and white robes of Kelemvor's clergy. A scar runs across his cheek, a reminder of how close he came to death when the Chapel of Sankt Elizabeth in Benwick Hollow fell.

This fellow has obviously seen many a day and night in service to the Eternal Order.  He stands like an ageless guardian, resolute and quiet in his black and white uniform and templar's helm.  The sun has bleached his tunic, and grains of sand have lodged themselves into the links of his chainmail, and yet he continues to stand firm.  His demeanor is grim, his aura that of one tried and true, and his hand often reaches down to touch the symbol of Kelemvor hanging at his belt, as if offering an unconscious prayer to his lord.

This finely crafted and blessed helmet is a part of the uniform of the Ravensword Regimet of the Eternal Order that is now stationed in the deserts of Khem. Under the left eye slit of the helmet the scales of justice upheld by a skeletal arm can be seen, the symbol of the Judge of the Dead.

These helmets were blessed by the priests of the Bastion of Sankt Elizabeth to grant the owner the strength and the consitution needed to do his or her duty in these lands.

This is one of the sacred full plates that have been crafted and blessed for the members of the Eternal Order of Lord Kelemvor. The ancient words of prayer carved into the armor are the source of its protective magic.

Due to the extreme heat in Khem these uniforms are seldom used, as the way they have been built may protect from the most devastating blows, but will bring the wearer down due to extreme exhaustion as they offer no protection from the sun.

These blades have their origin in the Nes'ek Crusade where they were first used against the tide of Undead. The holy symbol of Kelemvor is embossed on the pommel. Some of these swords were given to the allies of the Eternal Order.

OOC Note: This weapon can only be used by followers of Kelemvor, Jergal, Lathander, Tyr, Torm or Ilmater.

Jergal's Dogma: 

Each being has an eternal resting place that is chosen for him or her at the moment of creation. Life is a process of seeking that place and eternal rest. Existence is but a brief aberration in an eternity of death. Power, success, and joy are as transitory as weakness, failure, and misery. Only death is absolute, and then only at its appointed hour. Seek to bring order to the chaos of life, for in death there is finality and a fixedness of state. Be ready for death for it is at hand and uncompromising.

The heavy lid of this exquisitely-wrought marble sarcophagus bears upon it in near-full relief an artistically-rendered figure in full repose. The woman so depicted is tall and beautiful with shoulder-length hair and is dressed in the distinctive armor and tunic of the Eternal Order of Kelemvor. Her stone hands, though worn with age, are clasped firmly about the hilt of a golden sword which rests the length of her body.

We are the the Eternal Order, the right hand of lord Kelemvor, the instrument of His will, the gauntlet about His fist, the edge of His sword!

We are his most devoted servants, armoured in Faith, shielded by Devotion and armed with Purity of Purpose.

But greater even than these, we carry the light the pits of heresy to purge where ever it may be found!

Kelemvor's Dogma: 

Recognize that death is part of life. It is not an ending but a beginning, not a punishment but a necessity. Death is an orderly process without deceit, concealment, and randomness. Help others die with dignity at their appointed time and no sooner. Speak against those that would artificially prolong their life beyond natural limits, such as the undead. Do honor to the dead, for their strivings in life brought Faerun to where it is now. Forgetting them is to forget where we are now, and why. Let no human in all Faerun die a natural death without one of Kelemvor's clerics at her side.
